  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD051024",
      "title": "nano-LC/MS/MS analysis of Human Mesenteric lymph endogenous peptidome isolated from Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) subjects.",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "A compromised pathology of the intestinal barrier have been associated with a series of inflammatory conditions where the routine controls nutrient absorption and pathogens exclusion is lost to different degrees. When the epithelial barrier is compromised, bacteria and their products can attack the cells and cause inflammation, sometime leading to sepsis. Studying the lymph peptidome in inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) can offer valuable insights into the underlying mechanisms, disease progression, and potential therapeutic targets. To assess the efficiency of gut immune barrier, we collected the pre-nodal lymph from Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) subjects and performed a comprehensive peptidomic analysis. .  The current study is complementary extension of the proteomics signature found in DSS-induced colitis mouse model, providing an insight in the lymph composition inclined to an inflammatory phenotype which was also mirrored by a unique set of peptidome/degradome. Furthermore, the identified peptides mapped to a wide range of intracellular and extracellular pathways, encompassing cellular stress, apoptosis, and extracellular matrix degradation related pathways. A significant fraction of peptides was also found to be derived from bacterial origin with a predicted binding affinity to different MHC I and MHC II human haplotypes.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "Sample Processing Protocol:  The endogenous processed peptides from the human mesenteric were extracted and processed for nanoLC-MS/MS analysis using optimized protocols (Broggi et al., 2019; Clement et al., 2021; Clement et al., 2022) with modifications.  The total protein from the lymph collected from human patients were resuspended in 0.5 ml of sterile PBS buffer supplemented with a cocktail of protease inhibitors. Peptides were extracted using 0.2% TFA for 5 minutes, at 20\u00b0C.  Samples were then filtrated through a 10,000-Da cutoff filter device at 20\u00b0C for 30 minutes, desalted using pepClean C-18 spin columns, and eluted with 70% acetonitrile containing 0.1% TFA for further nanoLC/MS/MS analysis.  nanoLC MS/MS:  The endogenous processed peptides from the human mesenteric lymph and the tryptic digests of mouse mesenteric lymph samples were analyzed on a Q-Exactive HF quadrupole orbitrap mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA) coupled to an Easy nLC 1000 UHPLC (Thermo Fisher Scientific) through a nanoelectrospray ion source.  The mass spectrometer was operated using an already published protocol describing data\u2013dependent acquisition (DDA) and positive ionization mode (Seitzer and Searle, 2019).",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Proteomic database search The raw files from each biological replicate were filtered, de novo sequenced and assigned a protein ID using Peaks XPRO software (Bioinformatics Solutions, Waterloo, Canada), by searching against the Human (Homo Sapiens) revised SwissProt/UniProt (20,100 entries, August 2021). The search parameters were applied for LFQ analysis and two allowed missed cleavages at one or both peptide end.  The parent mass tolerance was set to 15 ppm using monoisotopic mass, and fragment ion mass tolerance was set at 0.06 Da.     Gene ontology, pathway enrichment of human lymph  Networks, functional analyses, and biochemical and cellular pathways were generated by employing the ingenuity pathway analysis (IPA; Ingenuity Systems, Redwood City, CA, USA) metascape platform. For networks generation, datasets containing gene identifiers (gene symbols) were uploaded into the IPA application where these molecules were overlaid onto a global molecular network contained in the Ingenuity Knowledge Base",
      "projectTags": [],
      "keywords": [
        "Lyph",
        "Peptidome",
        "Inflammatory bowel disease"
